# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: blend2d-graphics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] 2D computer graphics are mainly used in applications that were originally developed upon traditional printing and drawing technologies, such as typography, cartography, technical drawing, advertising, etc.
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] In many domains, such as desktop publishing, engineering, and business, a description of a document based on 2D computer graphics techniques can be much smaller than the corresponding digital image—often by a factor of 1/1000 or more.
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] This representation is also more flexible since it can be rendered at different resolutions to suit different output devices.
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] For these reasons, documents and illustrations are often stored or transmitted as 2D graphic files.
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] 2D computer graphics started in the 1950s, based on vector graphics devices.
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] These were largely supplanted by raster-based devices in the following decades.
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] The PostScript language and the X Window System protocol were landmark developments in the field.
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] 2D graphics models may combine geometric models (also called vector graphics), digital images (also called raster graphics), text to be typeset (defined by content, font style and size, color, position, and orientation), mathematical functions and equations, and more.
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] These components can be modified and manipulated by two-dimensional geometric transformations such as translation, rotation, and scaling.
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] In object-oriented graphics, the image is described indirectly by an object endowed with a self-rendering method—a procedure that assigns colors to the image pixels by an arbitrary algorithm.
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] Complex models can be built by combining simpler objects, in the paradigms of object-oriented programming.
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] In Euclidean geometry, a *translation (geometry)* moves every point a constant distance in a specified direction.
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] A translation can be described as a rigid motion: other rigid motions include rotations and reflections.
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] A translation can also be interpreted as the addition of a constant vector to every point, or as shifting the origin of the coordinate system.
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] If *T* is a translation, then the image of a subset *A* under the function *T* is the **translation** of *A* by *T*.
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] The translation of *A* by *T***v** is often written *A* + **v**.
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] In a Euclidean space, any translation is an isometry.
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] The set of all translations forms the translation group *T*, which is isomorphic to the space itself, and a normal subgroup of Euclidean group *E*(*n* ).
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] Since a translation is an affine transformation but not a linear transformation, homogeneous coordinates are normally used to represent the translation operator by a matrix and thus to make it linear.
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] Because addition of vectors is commutative, multiplication of translation matrices is therefore also commutative (unlike multiplication of arbitrary matrices).
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] In linear algebra, a *rotation matrix* is a matrix that is used to perform a rotation in Euclidean space.
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] rotates points in the *xy*-Cartesian plane counterclockwise through an angle *θ* about the origin of the Cartesian coordinate system.
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] To perform the rotation using a rotation matrix *R*, the position of each point must be represented by a column vector **v**, containing the coordinates of the point.
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] A rotated vector is obtained by using the matrix multiplication *R***v**.
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] Since matrix multiplication has no effect on the zero vector (i.e., on the coordinates of the origin), rotation matrices can only be used to describe rotations about the origin of the coordinate system.
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] Rotation matrices provide a simple algebraic description of such rotations, and are used extensively for computations in geometry, physics, and computer graphics.
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] In 2-dimensional space, a rotation can be simply described by an angle *θ* of rotation, but it can be also represented by the 4 entries of a rotation matrix with 2 rows and 2 columns.
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] In 3-dimensional space, every rotation can be interpreted as a rotation by a given angle about a single fixed axis of rotation (see Euler's rotation theorem), and hence it can be simply described by an angle and a vector with 3 entries.
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] However, it can also be represented by the 9 entries of a rotation matrix with 3 rows and 3 columns.
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] The notion of rotation is not commonly used in dimensions higher than 3; there is a notion of a *rotational displacement*, which can be represented by a matrix, but no associated single axis or angle.
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] Rotation matrices are square matrices, with real entries.
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] The set of all such matrices of size *n* forms a group, known as the special orthogonal group SO(*n*).
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] A convenient way to create a complex image is to start with a blank "canvas" raster map (an array of pixels, also known as a bitmap) filled with some uniform background color and then "draw", "paint" or "paste" simple patches of color onto it, in an appropriate order.
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] In particular the canvas may be the frame buffer for a computer display.
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] Text, shapes and lines are rendered with a client-specified color.
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] Many libraries and cards provide color gradients, which are handy for the generation of smoothly-varying backgrounds, shadow effects, etc.
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] The pixel colors can also be taken from a texture, e.g. a digital image (thus emulating rub-on screentones and the fabled *checker paint* which used to be available only in cartoons).
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] Painting a pixel with a given color usually replaces its previous color.
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] However, many systems support painting with transparent and translucent colors, which only modify the previous pixel values.
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] The two colors may also be combined in more complex ways, e.g. by computing their bitwise exclusive or.
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] This technique is known as *inverting color* or *color inversion*, and is often used in graphical user interfaces for highlighting, rubber-band drawing, and other volatile painting—since re-painting the same shapes with the same color will restore the original pixel values.
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] The models used in 2D computer graphics usually do not provide for three-dimensional shapes, or three-dimensional optical phenomena such as lighting, shadows, reflection, refraction, etc.
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] However, they usually can model multiple *layers* (conceptually of ink, paper, or film; opaque, translucent, or transparent—stacked in a specific order.
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] The ordering is usually defined by a single number (the layer's *depth*, or distance from the viewer).
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] Layered models are sometimes called "21⁄2-D computer graphics".
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] They make it possible to mimic traditional drafting and printing techniques based on film and paper, such as cutting and pasting; and allow the user to edit any layer without affecting the others.
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] For these reasons, they are used in most graphics editors.
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] Layered models also allow better spatial anti-aliasing of complex drawings and provide a sound model for certain techniques such as *mitered joints* and the even–odd rule.
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] Layered models are also used to allow the user to suppress unwanted information when viewing or printing a document, e.g. roads or railways from a map, certain process layers from an integrated circuit diagram, or hand annotations from a business letter.
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] In a layer-based model, the target image is produced by "painting" or "pasting" each layer, in order of decreasing depth, on the virtual canvas.
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] Conceptually, each layer is first rendered on its own, yielding a digital image with the desired resolution which is then painted over the canvas, pixel by pixel.
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] Fully transparent parts of a layer need not be rendered, of course.
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] The rendering and painting may be done in parallel, i.e., each layer pixel may be painted on the canvas as soon as it is produced by the rendering procedure.
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] Layers that consist of complex geometric objects (such as text or polylines) may be broken down into simpler elements (characters or line segments, respectively), which are then painted as separate layers, in some order.
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] However, this solution may create undesirable aliasing artifacts wherever two elements overlap the same pixel.
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] See also Portable Document Format#Layers.
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] Modern computer graphics card displays almost overwhelmingly use raster techniques, dividing the screen into a rectangular grid of pixels, due to the relatively low cost of raster-based video hardware as compared with vector graphic hardware.
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] Most graphic hardware has internal support for blitting operations or sprite drawing.
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] A co-processor dedicated to blitting is known as a *Blitter chip*.
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] Many graphical user interfaces (GUIs), including macOS, Microsoft Windows, or the X Window System, are primarily based on 2D graphical concepts.
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] Such software provides a visual environment for interacting with the computer, and commonly includes some form of window manager to aid the user in conceptually distinguishing between different applications.
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] The user interface within individual software applications is typically 2D in nature as well, due in part to the fact that most common input devices, such as the mouse, are constrained to two dimensions of movement.
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] 2D graphics are very important in the control peripherals such as printers, plotters, sheet cutting machines, etc.
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] They were also used in most early video games; and are still used for card and board games such as solitaire, chess, mahjongg, etc.
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] 2D graphics editors or *drawing programs* are application-level software for the creation of images, diagrams and illustrations by direct manipulation (through the mouse, graphics tablet, or similar device) of 2D computer graphics primitives.
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] These editors generally provide geometric primitives as well as digital images; and some even support procedural models.
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] The illustration is usually represented internally as a layered model, often with a hierarchical structure to make editing more convenient.
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] These editors generally output graphics files where the layers and primitives are separately preserved in their original form.
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] MacDraw, introduced in 1984 with the Macintosh line of computers, was an early example of this class; recent examples are the commercial products Adobe Illustrator and CorelDRAW, and the free editors such as xfig or Inkscape.
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] There are also many 2D graphics editors specialized for certain types of drawings such as electrical, electronic and VLSI diagrams, topographic maps, computer fonts, etc.
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] Image editors are specialized for the manipulation of digital images, mainly by means of free-hand drawing/painting and signal processing operations.
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] They typically use a direct-painting paradigm, where the user controls virtual pens, brushes, and other free-hand artistic instruments to apply paint to a virtual canvas.
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] Some image editors support a multiple-layer model; however, in order to support signal-processing operations like blurring each layer is normally represented as a digital image.
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] Therefore, any geometric primitives that are provided by the editor are immediately converted to pixels and painted onto the canvas.
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] The name *raster graphics editor* is sometimes used to contrast this approach to that of general editors which also handle *vector graphics*.
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] One of the first popular image editors was Apple's MacPaint, companion to MacDraw.
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] Modern examples are the free GIMP editor, and the commercial products Photoshop and Paint Shop Pro.
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] This class too includes many specialized editors—for medicine, remote sensing, digital photography, etc.
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] With the resurgence of 2D animation, free and proprietary software packages have become widely available for amateurs and professional animators.
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] With software like RETAS UbiArt Framework and Adobe After Effects, coloring and compositing can be done in less time.
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] Various approaches have been developed to aid and speed up the process of digital 2D animation.
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] For example, by generating vector artwork in a tool like Adobe Flash an artist may employ software-driven automatic coloring and in-betweening.
[src:blend2d-graphics/2d-computer-graphics] Programs like Blender or Adobe Substance allow the user to do either 3D animation, 2D animation or combine both in its software allowing experimentation with multiple forms of animation.
[src:blend2d-graphics/alpha-compositing] In computer graphics, **alpha compositing** or **alpha blending** is the process of combining one image with a background to create the appearance of partial or full transparency.
[src:blend2d-graphics/alpha-compositing] It is often useful to render picture elements (pixels) in separate passes or layers and then combine the resulting 2D images into a single, final image called the composite.
[src:blend2d-graphics/alpha-compositing] Compositing is used extensively in film when combining computer-rendered image elements with live footage.
[src:blend2d-graphics/alpha-compositing] Alpha blending is also used in 2D computer graphics to put rasterized foreground elements over a background.
[src:blend2d-graphics/alpha-compositing] In order to combine the picture elements of the images correctly, it is necessary to keep an associated *matte* for each element in addition to its color.
[src:blend2d-graphics/alpha-compositing] This matte layer contains the coverage information—the shape of the geometry being drawn—making it possible to distinguish between parts of the image where something was drawn and parts that are empty.
[src:blend2d-graphics/alpha-compositing] Although the most basic operation of combining two images is to put one over the other, there are many operations, or blend modes, that are used.
[src:blend2d-graphics/alpha-compositing] The concept of an alpha channel was introduced by Alvy Ray Smith and Ed Catmull in the late 1970s at the New York Institute of Technology Computer Graphics Lab.
[src:blend2d-graphics/alpha-compositing] Wallace derived the same straight **over** operator based on a physical reflectance/transmittance model in 1981.
[src:blend2d-graphics/alpha-compositing] A 1984 paper by Thomas Porter and Tom Duff introduced premultiplied alpha using a geometrical approach.
[src:blend2d-graphics/alpha-compositing] The use of the term *alpha* is explained by Smith as follows: "We called it that because of the classic linear interpolation formula $\alpha A+(1-\alpha )B$ that uses the Greek letter $\alpha$ (alpha) to control the amount of interpolation between, in this case, two images A and B".
[src:blend2d-graphics/alpha-compositing] That is, when compositing image A atop image B, the value of $\alpha$ in the formula is taken directly from A's alpha channel.
[src:blend2d-graphics/alpha-compositing] In a 2D image a color combination is stored for each picture element (pixel), often a combination of red, green and blue (RGB).
[src:blend2d-graphics/alpha-compositing] When alpha compositing is in use, each pixel has an additional numeric value stored in its **alpha channel**, with a value ranging from 0 to 1.
[src:blend2d-graphics/alpha-compositing] A value of 0 means that the pixel is fully transparent and the color in the pixel beneath will show through.
[src:blend2d-graphics/alpha-compositing] A value of 1 means that the pixel is fully opaque.
[src:blend2d-graphics/alpha-compositing] With the existence of an alpha channel, it is possible to express compositing image operations using a *compositing algebra*.
[src:blend2d-graphics/alpha-compositing] For example, given two images *A* and *B*, the most common compositing operation is to combine the images so that *A* appears in the foreground and *B* appears in the background.
[src:blend2d-graphics/alpha-compositing] This can be expressed as *A* **over** *B*.
[src:blend2d-graphics/alpha-compositing] The **over** operator is, in effect, the normal painting operation (see Painter's algorithm).
[src:blend2d-graphics/alpha-compositing] The **in** and **out** operators are the alpha compositing equivalent of clipping.
[src:blend2d-graphics/alpha-compositing] The two use only the alpha channel of the second image and ignore the color components.
[src:blend2d-graphics/alpha-compositing] In addition, **plus** defines additive blending.
[src:blend2d-graphics/alpha-compositing] If an alpha channel is used in an image, there are two common representations that are available: straight (unassociated) alpha and premultiplied (associated) alpha.
[src:blend2d-graphics/alpha-compositing] The most significant advantage of premultiplied alpha is that it allows for correct blending, interpolation, and filtering.
[src:blend2d-graphics/alpha-compositing] Ordinary interpolation without premultiplied alpha leads to RGB information leaking out of fully transparent (A=0) regions, even though this RGB information is ideally invisible.
[src:blend2d-graphics/alpha-compositing] When interpolating or filtering images with abrupt borders between transparent and opaque regions, this can result in borders of colors that were not visible in the original image.
[src:blend2d-graphics/alpha-compositing] Errors also occur in areas of semitransparency because the RGB components are not correctly weighted, giving incorrectly high weighting to the color of the more transparent (lower alpha) pixels.
[src:blend2d-graphics/alpha-compositing] Premultiplied alpha may also be used to allow regions of regular alpha blending (e.g. smoke) and regions with additive blending mode (e.g. flame and glitter effects) to be encoded within the same image.
[src:blend2d-graphics/alpha-compositing] This is represented by an RGBA triplet that express emission with no occlusion, such as (0.4, 0.3, 0.2, 0.0).
[src:blend2d-graphics/alpha-compositing] Another advantage of premultiplied alpha is performance; in certain situations, it can reduce the number of multiplication operations (e.g. if the image is used many times during later compositing).
[src:blend2d-graphics/alpha-compositing] The Porter–Duff operations have a simple form only in premultiplied alpha.
[src:blend2d-graphics/alpha-compositing] Some rendering pipelines expose a "straight alpha" API surface, but converts them into premultiplied alpha for performance.
[src:blend2d-graphics/alpha-compositing] One disadvantage of premultiplied alpha is that it can reduce the available relative precision in the RGB values when using integer or fixed-point representation for the color components.
[src:blend2d-graphics/alpha-compositing] This may cause a noticeable loss of quality if the color information is later brightened or if the alpha channel is removed.
[src:blend2d-graphics/alpha-compositing] In practice, this is not usually noticeable because during typical composition operations, such as OVER, the influence of the low-precision color information in low-alpha areas on the final output image (after composition) is correspondingly reduced.
[src:blend2d-graphics/alpha-compositing] This loss of precision also makes premultiplied images easier to compress using certain compression schemes, as they do not record the color variations hidden inside transparent regions, and can allocate fewer bits to encode low-alpha areas.
[src:blend2d-graphics/alpha-compositing] The same “limitations” of lower quantisation bit depths such as 8 bit per channel are also present in imagery without alpha, and this argument is problematic as a result.
[src:blend2d-graphics/alpha-compositing] Assuming that the pixel color is expressed using *straight* (non-premultiplied) RGBA tuples, a pixel value of (0, 0.7, 0, 0.5) implies a pixel that has 70% of the maximum green intensity and 50% opacity.
[src:blend2d-graphics/alpha-compositing] If the color were fully green, its RGBA would be (0, 1, 0, 0.5).
[src:blend2d-graphics/alpha-compositing] However, if this pixel uses premultiplied alpha, all of the RGB values (0, 0.7, 0) are multiplied, or scaled for occlusion, by the alpha value 0.5, which is appended to yield (0, 0.35, 0, 0.5).
[src:blend2d-graphics/alpha-compositing] In this case, the 0.35 value for the G channel actually indicates 70% green emission intensity (with 50% occlusion).
[src:blend2d-graphics/alpha-compositing] A pure green emission would be encoded as (0, 0.5, 0, 0.5).
[src:blend2d-graphics/alpha-compositing] Knowing whether a file uses straight or premultiplied alpha is essential to correctly process or composite it, as a different calculation is required.
[src:blend2d-graphics/alpha-compositing] Emission with no occlusion cannot be represented in straight alpha.
[src:blend2d-graphics/alpha-compositing] No conversion is available in this case.
[src:blend2d-graphics/alpha-compositing] The most popular image formats that support the alpha channel are PNG and TIFF.
[src:blend2d-graphics/alpha-compositing] GIF supports 1-bit transparency by designating one palette entry as transparent.
[src:blend2d-graphics/alpha-compositing] Support for alpha channels is present in some video codecs, such as Animation and Apple ProRes 4444 of the QuickTime format, or in the Techsmith multi-format codec.
[src:blend2d-graphics/alpha-compositing] This transformation better utilizes the limited number of bits in the encoded image by choosing $\gamma$ that better matches the non-linear human perception of luminance.
[src:blend2d-graphics/alpha-compositing] When combined with premultiplied alpha, pre-multiplication is done in linear space, prior to gamma compression.
[src:blend2d-graphics/alpha-compositing] Note that the alpha channel may or may not undergo gamma-correction, even when the color channels do.
[src:blend2d-graphics/alpha-compositing] Although used for similar purposes, transparent colors and image masks do not permit the smooth blending of the superimposed image pixels with those of the background (only whole image pixels or whole background pixels allowed).
[src:blend2d-graphics/alpha-compositing] A similar effect can be achieved with a 1-bit alpha channel, as found in the 16-bit RGBA high color mode of the Truevision TGA image file format and related TARGA and AT-Vista/NU-Vista display adapters' high color graphic mode.
[src:blend2d-graphics/alpha-compositing] This mode devotes 5 bits for every primary RGB color (15-bit RGB) plus a remaining bit as the "alpha channel".
[src:blend2d-graphics/alpha-compositing] Dithering can be used to simulate partial occlusion where only 1-bit alpha is available.
[src:blend2d-graphics/alpha-compositing] For some applications, a single alpha channel is not sufficient: a stained-glass window, for instance, requires a separate transparency channel for each RGB channel to model the red, green and blue transparency separately.
[src:blend2d-graphics/alpha-compositing] More alpha channels can be added for accurate spectral color filtration applications.
[src:blend2d-graphics/alpha-compositing] Some order-independent transparency methods replace the **over** operator with a commutative approximation.
[src:blend2d-graphics/anti-aliasing] In cel animation, animators can either add motion lines or create an object trail to give the impression of movement.
[src:blend2d-graphics/anti-aliasing] To solve the wagon-wheel effect without changing the sampling rate or wheel speed, animators could add a broken or discolored spoke to force viewer's visual system to make the correct connections between frames.
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] JIT compilation is a combination of the two traditional approaches to translation to machine code: ahead-of-time compilation (AOT), and interpretation, which combines some advantages and drawbacks of both.
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] Roughly, JIT compilation combines the speed of compiled code with the flexibility of interpretation, with the overhead of an interpreter and the additional overhead of compiling and linking (not just interpreting).
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] JIT compilation is a form of dynamic compilation, and allows adaptive optimization such as dynamic recompilation and microarchitecture-specific speedups.
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] Interpretation and JIT compilation are particularly suited for dynamic programming languages, as the runtime system can handle late-bound data types and enforce security guarantees.
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] The earliest published JIT compiler is generally attributed to work on LISP by John McCarthy in 1960.
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] Another early example was by Ken Thompson, who in 1968 gave one of the first applications of regular expressions, here for pattern matching in the text editor QED.
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] For speed, Thompson implemented regular expression matching by JITing to IBM 7094 code on the Compatible Time-Sharing System.
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] An influential technique for deriving compiled code from interpretation was pioneered by James G.
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] Mitchell in 1970, which he implemented for the experimental language *LC²*.
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] 1980) pioneered new aspects of JIT compilations.
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] For example, translation to machine code was done on demand, and the result was cached for later use.
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] When memory became scarce, the system would delete some of this code and regenerate it when it was needed again.
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] Sun's Self language improved these techniques extensively and was at one point the fastest Smalltalk system in the world, achieving up to half the speed of optimized C but with a fully object-oriented programming language.
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] Self was abandoned by Sun, but the research went into the Java language.
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] The term "Just-in-time compilation" was borrowed from the manufacturing term "Just in time" and popularized by Java, with James Gosling using the term from 1993.
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] Currently JITing is used by most implementations of the Java virtual machine, as HotSpot builds on, and extensively uses, this research base.
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] The HP project Dynamo was an experimental JIT compiler where the "bytecode" format and the machine code format were the same; the system optimized PA-8000 machine code.
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] In November 2020, PHP 8.0 introduced a JIT compiler.
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] In October 2024, CPython introduced an experimental JIT compiler.
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] In a bytecode-compiled system, source code is translated to an intermediate representation known as bytecode.
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] Bytecode is not the machine code for any particular computer, and may be portable among computer architectures.
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] The bytecode may then be interpreted by, or run on a virtual machine.
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] The JIT compiler reads the bytecodes in many sections (or in full, rarely) and compiles them dynamically into machine code so the program can run faster.
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] This can be done per-file, per-function or even on any arbitrary code fragment; the code can be compiled when it is about to be executed (hence the name "just-in-time"), and then cached and reused later without needing to be recompiled.
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] By contrast, a traditional *interpreted virtual machine* will simply interpret the bytecode, generally with much lower performance.
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] Some *interpreter*s even interpret source code, without the step of first compiling to bytecode, with even worse performance.
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] *Statically-compiled code* or *native code* is compiled prior to deployment.
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] A *dynamic compilation environment* is one in which the compiler can be used during execution.
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] The deployed bytecode is portable, unlike native code.
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] Since the runtime has control over the compilation, like interpreted bytecode, it can run in a secure sandbox.
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] Compilers from bytecode to machine code are easier to write, because the portable bytecode compiler has already done much of the work.
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] JIT code generally offers far better performance than interpreters.
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] The system is able to collect statistics about how the program is actually running in the environment it is in, and it can rearrange and recompile for optimum performance.
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] However, some static compilers can also take profile information as input.
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] The system can do global code optimizations (e.g. inlining of library functions) without losing the advantages of dynamic linking and without the overheads inherent to static compilers and linkers.
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] With just-in-time compilation in many cases this processing can be moved out of loops, often giving large increases of speed.
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] Although this is possible with statically compiled garbage collected languages, a bytecode system can more easily rearrange executed code for better cache utilization.
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] However, a special type of "JIT" may potentially *not* target the physical machine's CPU architecture, but rather an optimized VM bytecode where limitations on raw machine code prevail, especially where that bytecode's VM eventually leverages a JIT to native code.
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] JIT causes a slight to noticeable delay in the initial execution of an application, due to the time taken to load and compile the input code.
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] Sometimes this delay is called "startup time delay" or "warm-up time".
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] In general, the more optimization JIT performs, the better the code it will generate, but the initial delay will also increase.
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] A JIT compiler therefore has to make a trade-off between the compilation time and the quality of the code it hopes to generate.
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] Startup time can include increased IO-bound operations in addition to JIT compilation: for example, the *rt.jar* class data file for the Java virtual machine (JVM) is 40 MB and the JVM must seek a lot of data in this contextually huge file.
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] One possible optimization, used by Sun's HotSpot Java virtual machine, is to combine interpretation and JIT compilation.
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] The application code is initially interpreted, but the JVM monitors which sequences of bytecode are frequently executed and translates them to machine code for direct execution on the hardware.
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] For bytecode which is executed only a few times, this saves the compilation time and reduces the initial latency; for frequently executed bytecode, JIT compilation is used to run at high speed, after an initial phase of slow interpretation.
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] Further, since a program spends most time executing a minority of its code, the reduced compilation time is significant.
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] Finally, during the initial code interpretation, execution statistics can be collected before compilation, which helps to perform better optimization.
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] The correct tradeoff can vary due to circumstances.
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] For example, Sun's Java virtual machine has two major modes—client and server.
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] In client mode, minimal compilation and optimization is performed, to reduce startup time.
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] In server mode, extensive compilation and optimization is performed, to maximize performance once the application is running by sacrificing startup time.
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] Other Java just-in-time compilers have used a runtime measurement of the number of times a method has executed combined with the bytecode size of a method as a heuristic to decide when to compile.
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] Still another uses the number of times executed combined with the detection of loops.
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] In general, it is much harder to accurately predict which methods to optimize in short-running applications than in long-running ones.
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] Native Image Generator (Ngen) by Microsoft is another approach at reducing the initial delay.
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] Ngen pre-compiles (or "pre-JITs") bytecode in a Common Intermediate Language image into machine native code.
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] As a result, no runtime compilation is needed. .NET Framework 2.0 shipped with Visual Studio 2005 runs Ngen on all of the Microsoft dynamic-link library (DLL) files right after installing.
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] Pre-jitting provides a way to reduce startup time.
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] However, the quality of code it generates may be lower than the one that is JITed, for the same reasons why code compiled statically, without profile-guided optimization, cannot be as good as JIT compiled code in the extreme case: the lack of profiling data to drive, for instance, inline caching.
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] There also exist Java implementations that combine an AOT (ahead-of-time) compiler with either a JIT compiler (Excelsior JET) or interpreter (GNU Compiler for Java).
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] JIT compilation may not reliably achieve its goal, namely entering a steady state of improved performance after a short initial warmup period.
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] Across eight different virtual machines, Barrett et al.
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] (2017) measured six widely used microbenchmarks which are commonly used by virtual machine implementors as optimisation targets, running them repeatedly within a single process execution.
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] Even where an improved steady-state was reached, it sometimes took many hundreds of iterations.
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] (2022) instead focused on the HotSpot virtual machine but with a much wider array of benchmarks, finding that 10.9% of process executions failed to reach a steady state of performance, and 43.5% of benchmarks did not consistently attain a steady state across multiple executions.
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] JIT compilation fundamentally uses executable data, and thus poses security challenges and possible exploits.
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] Implementation of JIT compilation consists of compiling source code or byte code to machine code and executing it.
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] This is generally done directly in memory: the JIT compiler outputs the machine code directly into memory and immediately executes it, rather than outputting it to disk and then invoking the code as a separate program, as in usual ahead of time compilation.
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] In modern architectures this runs into a problem due to executable space protection: arbitrary memory cannot be executed, as otherwise there is a potential security hole.
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] Thus memory must be marked as executable; for security reasons this should be done *after* the code has been written to memory, and marked read-only, as writable/executable memory is a security hole (see W^X).
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] For instance Firefox's JIT compiler for JavaScript introduced this protection in a release version with Firefox 46.
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] JIT spraying is a class of computer security exploits that use JIT compilation for heap spraying: the resulting memory is then executable, which allows an exploit if execution can be moved into the heap.
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] JIT compilation can be applied to some programs, or can be used for certain capacities, particularly dynamic capacities such as regular expressions.
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] For example, a text editor may compile a regular expression provided at runtime to machine code to allow faster matching: this cannot be done ahead of time, as the pattern is only provided at runtime.
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] Several modern runtime environments rely on JIT compilation for high-speed code execution, including most implementations of Java, together with Microsoft's .NET.
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] Similarly, many regular-expression libraries feature JIT compilation of regular expressions, either to bytecode or to machine code.
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] JIT compilation is also used in some emulators, in order to translate machine code from one CPU architecture to another.
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] A common implementation of JIT compilation is to first have AOT compilation to bytecode (virtual machine code), known as *bytecode compilation*, and then have JIT compilation to machine code (dynamic compilation), rather than interpretation of the bytecode.
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] This improves the runtime performance compared to interpretation, at the cost of lag due to compilation.
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] JIT compilers translate continuously, as with interpreters, but caching of compiled code minimizes lag on future execution of the same code during a given run.
[src:blend2d-graphics/just-in-time-compilation] Since only part of the program is compiled, there is significantly less lag than if the entire program were compiled prior to execution.
[src:blend2d-graphics/rasterisation] In computer graphics, **rasterisation** (British English) or **rasterization** (American English) is the task of taking an image described in a vector graphics format (shapes) and converting it into a raster image which represents the original image.
[src:blend2d-graphics/rasterisation] The rasterized image may then be displayed on a computer display, video display or printer, or stored in a bitmap file format.
[src:blend2d-graphics/rasterisation] Rasterization may refer to the technique of drawing 3D models, or to the conversion of 2D rendering primitives, such as polygons and line segments, into a rasterized format.
[src:blend2d-graphics/rasterisation] The term "rasterisation" comes from German *Raster* 'grid, pattern, schema' and Latin *rāstrum* 'scraper, rake'.
[src:blend2d-graphics/rasterisation] Bresenham's line algorithm is an example of an algorithm used to rasterize lines.
[src:blend2d-graphics/rasterisation] Algorithms such as the midpoint circle algorithm are used to render circles onto a pixelated canvas.
[src:blend2d-graphics/rasterisation] Polygons are a common representation of digital 3D models.
[src:blend2d-graphics/rasterisation] Before rasterization, individual polygons are triangulated - therefore, a typical problem to solve in 3D rasterization is rasterization of a triangle.
[src:blend2d-graphics/rasterisation] 2. no pixel is rasterized more than once, i.e. the rasterized triangles don't overlap.
[src:blend2d-graphics/rasterisation] This is to guarantee that the result doesn't depend on the order in which the triangles are rasterized.
[src:blend2d-graphics/rasterisation] Overdrawing pixels can also mean wasting computing power on pixels that would be overwritten.
[src:blend2d-graphics/rasterisation] This leads to establishing **rasterization rules** to guarantee the above conditions.
[src:blend2d-graphics/rasterisation] 2. its center lies exactly on the triangle edge (or multiple edges in case of corners) – that is (or, in case of corners, all are), either the *top* or *left* edge.
[src:blend2d-graphics/rasterisation] A *top* edge is an edge that is exactly horizontal and lies above other edges, and a *left* edge is a non-horizontal edge that is on the left side of the triangle.
[src:blend2d-graphics/rasterisation] This rule decides which triangle a pixel on a boundary belongs to.
[src:blend2d-graphics/rasterisation] It is implemented by Direct3D and OpenGL (although the specification here only requires a consistent rule).
[src:blend2d-graphics/rasterisation] Rasterization is one of the typical techniques of rendering 3D models.
[src:blend2d-graphics/rasterisation] Compared with other rendering techniques such as ray tracing, rasterization is extremely fast and therefore used in most realtime 3D engines.
[src:blend2d-graphics/rasterisation] However, rasterization is simply the process of computing the mapping from scene geometry to pixels and does not prescribe a particular way to compute the color of those pixels.
[src:blend2d-graphics/rasterisation] The specific color of each pixel is assigned by a pixel shader (which in modern GPUs is completely programmable).
[src:blend2d-graphics/rasterisation] Shading may take into account physical effects such as light position, their approximations or purely artistic intent.
[src:blend2d-graphics/rasterisation] The process of rasterizing 3D models onto a 2D plane for display on a computer screen ("screen space") is often carried out by fixed function (non-programmable) hardware within the graphics pipeline.
[src:blend2d-graphics/rasterisation] This is because there is no motivation for modifying the techniques for rasterization used at render time and a special-purpose system allows for high efficiency.
[src:blend2d-graphics/rasterisation] The quality of rasterization can be improved by antialiasing, which creates "smooth" edges.
[src:blend2d-graphics/rasterisation] Sub-pixel precision is a method which takes into account positions on a finer scale than the pixel grid and can produce different results even if the endpoints of a primitive fall into same pixel coordinates, producing smoother movement animations.
[src:blend2d-graphics/rasterisation] Simple or older hardware, such as PlayStation 1, lacked sub-pixel precision in 3D rasterization.
[src:blend2d-graphics/vector-graphics] While vector hardware has largely disappeared in favor of raster-based monitors and printers, vector data and software continue to be widely used, especially when a high degree of geometric precision is required, and when complex information can be decomposed into simple geometric primitives.
[src:blend2d-graphics/vector-graphics] Thus, it is the preferred model for domains such as engineering, architecture, surveying, 3D rendering, and typography, but is entirely inappropriate for applications such as photography and remote sensing, where raster is more effective and efficient.
[src:blend2d-graphics/vector-graphics] Some application domains, such as geographic information systems (GIS) and graphic design, use both vector and raster graphics at times, depending on purpose.
[src:blend2d-graphics/vector-graphics] Vector graphics are based on the mathematics of analytic or coordinate geometry, and is not related to other mathematical uses of the term vector.
[src:blend2d-graphics/vector-graphics] This can lead to some confusion in disciplines in which both meanings are used.
[src:blend2d-graphics/vector-graphics] The logical data model of vector graphics is based on the mathematics of coordinate geometry, in which shapes are defined as a set of points in a two- or three-dimensional cartesian coordinate system, as *p* = (*x, y*) or *p* = (*x, y, z*).
[src:blend2d-graphics/vector-graphics] Because almost all shapes consist of an infinite number of points, the vector model defines a limited set of geometric primitives that can be specified using a finite sample of salient points called vertices.
[src:blend2d-graphics/vector-graphics] For example, a square can be unambiguously defined by the locations of three of its four corners, from which the software can interpolate the connecting boundary lines and the interior space.
[src:blend2d-graphics/vector-graphics] Because it is a regular shape, a square could also be defined by the location of one corner, a size (width=height), and a rotation angle.
[src:blend2d-graphics/vector-graphics] In many vector datasets, each shape can be combined with a set of properties.
[src:blend2d-graphics/vector-graphics] The most common are visual characteristics, such as color, line weight, or dash pattern.
[src:blend2d-graphics/vector-graphics] In systems in which shapes represent real-world features, such as GIS and BIM, a variety of attributes of each represented feature can be stored, such as name, age, size, and so on.
[src:blend2d-graphics/vector-graphics] In some Vector data, especially in GIS, information about topological relationships between objects may be represented in the data model, such as tracking the connections between road segments in a transport network.
[src:blend2d-graphics/vector-graphics] If a dataset stored in one vector file format is converted to another file format that supports all the primitive objects used in that particular image, then the conversion can be lossless.
[src:blend2d-graphics/vector-graphics] Vector-based devices, such as the vector CRT and the pen plotter, directly control a drawing mechanism to produce geometric shapes.
[src:blend2d-graphics/vector-graphics] Since vector display devices can define a line by dealing with just two points (that is, the coordinates of each end of the line), the device can reduce the total amount of data it must deal with by organizing the image in terms of pairs of points.
[src:blend2d-graphics/vector-graphics] Vector graphic displays were first used in 1958 by the US SAGE air defense system.
[src:blend2d-graphics/vector-graphics] Vector graphics systems were retired from the U.S. en route air traffic control in 1999.
[src:blend2d-graphics/vector-graphics] Vector graphics were also used on the TX-2 at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology Lincoln Laboratory by computer graphics pioneer Ivan Sutherland to run his program Sketchpad in 1963.
[src:blend2d-graphics/vector-graphics] Subsequent vector graphics systems, most of which iterated through dynamically modifiable stored lists of drawing instructions, include the IBM 2250, Imlac PDS-1, and DEC GT40.
[src:blend2d-graphics/vector-graphics] There was a video game console that used vector graphics called Vectrex as well as various arcade games like *Asteroids*, *Space Wars*, *Tempest* and many cinematronics titles such as *Rip Off*, and *Tail Gunner* using vector monitors.
[src:blend2d-graphics/vector-graphics] Storage scope displays, such as the Tektronix 4014, could display vector images but not modify them without first erasing the display.
[src:blend2d-graphics/vector-graphics] However, these were never as widely used as the raster-based scanning displays used for television, and had largely disappeared by the mid-1980s except for specialized applications.
[src:blend2d-graphics/vector-graphics] Plotters used in technical drawing still draw vectors directly to paper by moving a pen as directed through the two-dimensional space of the paper.
[src:blend2d-graphics/vector-graphics] However, as with monitors, these have largely been replaced by the wide-format printer that prints a raster image (which may be rendered from vector data).
[src:blend2d-graphics/vector-graphics] Because this model is useful in a variety of application domains, many different software programs have been created for drawing, manipulating, and visualizing vector graphics.
[src:blend2d-graphics/vector-graphics] While these are all based on the same basic vector data model, they can interpret and structure shapes very differently, using very different file formats.
[src:blend2d-graphics/vector-graphics] Vector graphics are commonly found today in the SVG, WMF, EPS, PDF, CDR or AI types of graphic file formats, and are intrinsically different from the more common raster graphics file formats such as JPEG, PNG, APNG, GIF, WebP, BMP and MPEG4.
[src:blend2d-graphics/vector-graphics] The World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) standard for vector graphics is Scalable Vector Graphics (SVG).
[src:blend2d-graphics/vector-graphics] The standard is complex and has been relatively slow to be established at least in part owing to commercial interests.
[src:blend2d-graphics/vector-graphics] Many web browsers now have some support for rendering SVG data but full implementations of the standard are still comparatively rare.
[src:blend2d-graphics/vector-graphics] In recent years, SVG has become a significant format that is completely independent of the resolution of the rendering device, typically a printer or display monitor.
[src:blend2d-graphics/vector-graphics] SVG files are essentially printable text that describes both straight and curved paths, as well as other attributes.
[src:blend2d-graphics/vector-graphics] Wikipedia prefers SVG for images such as simple maps, line illustrations, coats of arms, and flags, which generally are not like photographs or other continuous-tone images.
[src:blend2d-graphics/vector-graphics] Rendering SVG requires conversion to a raster format at a resolution appropriate for the current task.
[src:blend2d-graphics/vector-graphics] SVG is also a format for animated graphics.
[src:blend2d-graphics/vector-graphics] There is also a version of SVG for mobile phones called SVGT (SVG Tiny version).
[src:blend2d-graphics/vector-graphics] These images can count links and also exploit anti-aliasing.
[src:blend2d-graphics/vector-graphics] They can also be displayed as wallpaper.
[src:blend2d-graphics/vector-graphics] CAD software uses its own vector data formats, usually proprietary formats created by software vendors, such as Autodesk's DWG and public exchange formats such as DXF.
[src:blend2d-graphics/vector-graphics] Modern displays and printers are raster devices; vector formats have to be converted to a raster format (bitmaps – pixel arrays) before they can be rendered (displayed or printed).
[src:blend2d-graphics/vector-graphics] The size of the bitmap/raster-format file generated by the conversion will depend on the resolution required, but the size of the vector file generating the bitmap/raster file will always remain the same.
[src:blend2d-graphics/vector-graphics] Thus, it is easy to convert from a vector file to a range of bitmap/raster file formats but it is much more difficult to go in the opposite direction, especially if subsequent editing of the vector picture is required.
[src:blend2d-graphics/vector-graphics] It might be an advantage to save an image created from a vector source file as a bitmap/raster format, because different systems have different (and incompatible) vector formats, and some might not support vector graphics at all.
[src:blend2d-graphics/vector-graphics] However, once a file is converted from the vector format, it is likely to be bigger, and it loses the advantage of scalability without loss of resolution.
[src:blend2d-graphics/vector-graphics] It will also no longer be possible to edit individual parts of the image as discrete objects.
[src:blend2d-graphics/vector-graphics] The file size of a vector graphic image depends on the number of graphic elements it contains; it is a list of descriptions.
[src:blend2d-graphics/vector-graphics] Vector art is ideal for printing since the art is made from a series of mathematical curves; it will print very crisply even when resized.
[src:blend2d-graphics/vector-graphics] For instance, one can print a vector logo on a small sheet of copy paper, and then enlarge the same vector logo to billboard size and keep the same crisp quality.
[src:blend2d-graphics/vector-graphics] A low-resolution raster graphic would blur or pixelate excessively if it were enlarged from business card size to billboard size.
[src:blend2d-graphics/vector-graphics] If we regard typographic characters as images, then the same considerations that we have made for graphics apply even to the composition of written text for printing (typesetting).
[src:blend2d-graphics/vector-graphics] Older character sets were stored as bitmaps.
[src:blend2d-graphics/vector-graphics] Therefore, to achieve maximum print quality they had to be used at a given resolution only; these font formats are said to be non-scalable.
[src:blend2d-graphics/vector-graphics] High-quality typography is nowadays based on character drawings (fonts) which are typically stored as vector graphics, and as such are scalable to any size.
[src:blend2d-graphics/vector-graphics] Examples of these vector formats for characters are Postscript fonts and TrueType fonts.
[src:blend2d-graphics/vector-graphics] For example, consider a circle of radius *r*.
[src:blend2d-graphics/vector-graphics] Vector formats are not always appropriate in graphics work and also have numerous disadvantages.
[src:blend2d-graphics/vector-graphics] For example, devices such as cameras and scanners produce essentially continuous-tone raster graphics that are impractical to convert into vectors, and so for this type of work, an image editor will operate on the pixels rather than on drawing objects defined by mathematical expressions.
[src:blend2d-graphics/vector-graphics] Comprehensive graphics tools will combine images from vector and raster sources, and may provide editing tools for both, since some parts of an image could come from a camera source, and others could have been drawn using vector tools.
[src:blend2d-graphics/vector-graphics] Some authors have criticized the term *vector graphics* as being confusing.
[src:blend2d-graphics/vector-graphics] In particular, *vector graphics* does not simply refer to graphics described by Euclidean vectors.
[src:blend2d-graphics/vector-graphics] Some authors have proposed to use *object-oriented graphics* instead.
[src:blend2d-graphics/vector-graphics] However this term can also be confusing as it can be read as any kind of graphics implemented using object-oriented programming.
[src:blend2d-graphics/vector-graphics] Vector graphics editors typically allow translation, rotation, mirroring, stretching, skewing, affine transformations, changing of z-order (loosely, what's in front of what) and combination of primitives into more complex objects.
[src:blend2d-graphics/vector-graphics] More sophisticated transformations include set operations on closed shapes (union, difference, intersection, etc.).
[src:blend2d-graphics/vector-graphics] In SVG, the composition operations are based on alpha composition.
[src:blend2d-graphics/vector-graphics] Vector graphics are ideal for simple or composite drawings that need to be device-independent, or do not need to achieve photo-realism.
[src:blend2d-graphics/vector-graphics] For example, the PostScript and PDF page description languages use a vector graphics model.
[src:blend2d-graphics/vector-graphics] Many stock photo websites provide vectorized versions of hosted images, while specific repositories specialize in vector images given their growing popularity among graphic designers.
